    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure! L1 regularization, also known as Lasso, adds a penalty equal to the absolute value of the magnitude of coefficients. This can lead to some coefficients being exactly zero, which means it can help with feature selection. On the other hand, L2 regularization, also known as Ridge, adds a penalty equal to the square of the magnitude of coefficients. This tends to shrink the coefficients towards zero but rarely exactly zero, which can help prevent overfitting by keeping all features in the model but with smaller coefficients. In essence, L1 regularization can help you find a simpler model with fewer features, while L2 regularization helps you find a more stable model with all features included.",
